---
import BaseLayout from '../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About — Propaedia" description="About this web edition of the Propaedia Outline of Knowledge">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8">About This Project</h1>

    <div class="prose-propaedia">
      <h2>The Propaedia</h2>
      <p>
        The <em>Propaedia</em>, or "Outline of Knowledge," is one of three parts of the
        <em>Encyclopaedia Britannica</em> (15th edition). Created under the direction of
        Mortimer J. Adler, it provides a systematic classification of all human knowledge
        organized into <strong>10 Parts</strong>, <strong>41 Divisions</strong>, and
        <strong>177 Sections</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unlike a traditional encyclopedia arranged alphabetically, the Propaedia presents
        knowledge hierarchically — showing how subjects relate to one another within the
        broader landscape of human understanding.
      </p>

      <h2>This Web Edition</h2>
      <p>
        This site turns the Propaedia into an interactive reading guide. The original
        knowledge hierarchy is preserved and enriched with three layers of reading
        recommendations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Oxford Very Short Introductions</strong> — curated book recommendations matched to each Section's subject matter, with relevance scoring and filtering by outline topic</li>
        <li><strong>Wikipedia Vital Articles</strong> — mapped articles from Wikipedia's curated list of essential topics, scored by relevance to each Section</li>
        <li><strong>Macropaedia articles</strong> — the original Britannica reading lists from the print edition</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each Section page also includes the original hierarchical subject outline with
        cross-references linking related Sections across the ten Parts.
      </p>

      <h2>The Circle of Learning</h2>
      <p>
        The homepage features an interactive circle navigator based on Adler's concept
        that the ten Parts of knowledge form a circle rather than a list. You can drag
        to rotate the ring, pull any Part into the centre to reframe the circle around
        it, and explore how different fields connect.
      </p>
      <p>
        When a Part is placed at the centre and another is rotated to the top, the panel
        below the circle shows how they connect — both through cross-referenced Sections
        and through <strong>bridge readings</strong>, books and articles that were
        independently recommended for Sections in both Parts. These surface resources that
        connect two fields of knowledge, ranked by how many Sections across both Parts
        recommend them.
      </p>

      <h2>Reading Tools</h2>
      <p>
        A <strong>reading preference</strong> setting in the sidebar lets you choose your
        preferred reading type (Oxford VSI, Wikipedia, BBC In Our Time, or Macropaedia). This controls which
        recommendations open and scroll into view when you click an outline item, and which
        bridge readings are shown first on the homepage.
      </p>
      <p>
        A <strong>reading checklist</strong> lets you mark books, articles, and episodes as done.
        Progress is saved locally in your browser and reflected across the site — checked
        items are excluded from bridge recommendations on the homepage, and checkboxes
        appear on individual reading pages.
      </p>

      <h2>Reading Recommendations</h2>
      <p>
        The Oxford VSI, Wikipedia, and BBC In Our Time recommendations are matched to Sections using a
        combination of keyword analysis and AI-generated mappings. Each recommendation
        includes a rationale explaining why it was matched. Clicking an outline item
        filters the recommendations to show only those relevant to that specific topic.
      </p>

      <details class="mt-2 rounded-lg border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 px-4 py-3">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700">How relevance is calculated</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-600">
          <p>
            Each book or article receives a relevance score based on how closely it
            relates to the Section you are viewing. A resource whose title directly
            names the topic scores highest. Beyond the title, the scoring considers
            subject keywords and how well the resource's description aligns with the
            topics covered in the Section's outline.
          </p>
          <p>
            When you click an outline item to filter the list, the scoring also
            considers the sub-topics beneath that item. A resource that touches many
            of those sub-topics ranks higher than one that strongly matches just one
            narrow area.
          </p>
          <p>
            The relevance percentage shown on each card is relative — the best-scoring
            resource in the current view is always shown as 100%, and the others are
            scaled proportionally.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <p>
        The VSI catalogue and keyword data were last updated in <strong>March 2025</strong>,
        covering 793 titles from the Oxford Very Short Introductions series.
        The Wikipedia Vital Articles data was last updated in <strong>March 2026</strong>,
        covering 998 articles.
      </p>

      <h2>Technical Details</h2>
      <p>
        This site is built with <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a> and
        <a href="https://preactjs.com">Preact</a>, uses static site generation for fast
        loading, and is hosted on GitHub Pages. Search is powered by
        <a href="https://pagefind.app">Pagefind</a>. All data is processed at build time
        — there are no external API calls or server dependencies at runtime.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
